NEW YORK (AP) — Omicron is shining a spotlight on the disparities between who gets paid sick days and who doesn’t. Nearly 80% of all private sector workers get at least one paid sick day, according to a national compensation survey of employee benefits conducted in March by the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. But many workers are vulnerable, particularly those in the low income bracket.Here is a look at the breakdown of who gets paid sick days: BY INCOME BRACKET:Bottom 10%: 33%Top 10%: 95%BY EMPLOYMENT STATUS:Part-time: 48%Full-time: 87%BY OCCUPATION:Financial Activities: 94%Education and Health Services: 85%Construction: 69%Retail Trade: 67%Leisure and Hospitality: 50%BY SIZE OF EMPLOYER:1 to 49 workers: 68%500 workers or more: 91%SOURCE: U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics